2026-03-02 12:02:53,330 - ThreadPoolExecutor-0_0 - INFO - {'status': 'OK', 'InterviewDetails': {'Id': 16225, 'TestUserId': 3838065, 'EventId': 17924, 'ApplicantId': 1407881, 'Experience': 3, 'FavoriteProject': 'E-commerce platform redesign', 'IsEnded': True, 'InterviewDate': '2025-12-02T16:55:38', 'DetailedFeedback': [], 'CommonFeedback': [], 'CommonFeedbackScore': '0.0', 'OverAllFeedback': 'Good Profile', 'Transcripts': [{'question': 'Interviewer: Hi, Good day! welcome to interview, brief about yourself', 'answer': "Candidate: Hi, I'manobis Nirmal and currently I'm working at XYZ. I have experience with UI designing, especially with Figma and Adobe Illustrator. I have some experience in photo editing and video editing as well. For photo and video, I use Premiere Pro and Photoshop. "}, {'question': "Interviewer: That's an interesting background, Norval! Now, can you tell me what role ChromeDriver plays in automation testing?", 'answer': 'Candidate: Yes sure, so ChromeDriver is basically a software which helps you to execute the task that it will retain on your code and help to execute the task by connecting your code with a browser, real time browser and in this case, especially the Chrome browser. So whenever you run a code, you need the Chrome browser to execute the same task, ChromeDriver to execute the same task in a browser. '}, {'question': "Interviewer: That's an interesting approach! Now, how would you approach testing the user interface of a redesigned e-commerce platform to ensure it meets usability and accessibility standards?", 'answer': 'Candidate: Okay, so to check the usability and accessibility standards, there are a couple of ways that you can proceed when you are building a component or building a software specifically. So first, you first generally create the software, you do the basic testing, once the basic testing is done and the bugs are gone, then you create a beta version of it, and then you have two options, you can make it available for the public and gather, make the beta version available for the public and gather info from there, I mean, and the feedbacks will help you to get the user accessibility and stabilize the software. And the second thing you can do is, with your testing team only, you do a UI UX testing and just to make sure that the things are working or not, from there also you can gather feedback and make the changes as per needed. '}, {'question': "Interviewer: That's an interesting approach! Now, how would you approach testing the user interface of a redesigned e-commerce platform to ensure it meets usability and accessibility standards?", 'answer': 'Candidate: Okay, so to check the usability and accessibility standards, there are a couple of ways that you can proceed when you are building a component or building a software specifically. So first, you first generally create the software, you do the basic testing, once the basic testing is done and the bugs are gone, then you create a beta version of it, and then you have two options, you can make it available for the public and gather, make the beta version available for the public and gather info from there, I mean, and the feedbacks will help you to get the user accessibility and stabilize the software. And the second thing you can do is, with your testing team only, you do a UI UX testing and just to make sure that the things are working or not, from there also you can gather feedback and make the changes as per needed. '}, {'question': "Interviewer: Thanks for sharing! Let's move on to how you decide which test cases to execute manually.", 'answer': 'Candidate: So there are various ways where we can get to determine that which of the test cases that we have to execute manually. In the initial state, basically all of the test cases that we check manually for the first cycle. Then we determine that which of the test cases can be automated, which are very much repetitive and can be handled by automation. And where no human interaction is required in those type of test cases, we automate. And rest of the test cases that are available where human intervention is very much needed and not possible to repeat the task using bot or something. Those cases we generally handle by manual testing. '}, {'question': 'Interviewer: Good point. How do you handle test cases that require complex human judgment or are prone to frequent changes?', 'answer': "Candidate: So, there are patterns, like there are few test cases, like suppose, test cases where human feedback is needed in different ways, so those cases where a human audio video interactive session is needed, those type of test cases you just can't replicate using automated bots or automated codes, you have to be there, you have to attend it yourself, so those type of test cases normally, the cases where manual regulation is needed. "}, {'question': 'Interviewer: How does using smart objects in Photoshop help make design updates more flexible and efficient?', 'answer': "Candidate: Smart Objects in Photoshop make design updates super flexible and efficient. They let you edit images non-destructively, so resizing or transforming won't ruin the original quality. You can link to external files, and when they update, your design automatically updates too. Plus, you can stack filters and adjust them later without losing the original data. Working with multiple instances of the same asset becomes much easier, saving time and effort. It's perfect for maintaining consistency and flexibility across a project. "}, {'question': "Interviewer: {'question': 'Write a C program to find the sum of all elements in an integer array using recursion. The function should take an array and its size as input and return the sum of its elements.', 'code': '#include <stdio.h>\\n\\nint sumArray(int arr[], int size);\\n\\nint main() {\\n    // Code goes here\\n    return 0;\\n}', 'output': 'The program should output the sum of all elements in the array.', 'example': {'input': 'Array: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5], Size: 5', 'output': 'Sum: 15'}}", 'answer': 'Candidate: #include <stdio.h>\n\nint sum(int arr[], int size) {\n    if (size == 0) {\n        return 0;\n    }\n    return arr[size - 1] + sum(arr, size - 1);\n}\n\nint main() {\n    int arr[] = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};\n    int size = sizeof(arr) / sizeof(arr[0]);\n    int result = sum(arr, size);\n    printf("Sum: %d\\n", result);\n    return 0;\n} '}, {'question': "Interviewer: {'question': 'Write a C program to reverse an array of integers using recursion. The function should take an array and its size as input and modify the array in place.', 'code': '#include <stdio.h>\\n\\nvoid reverseArray(int arr[], int start, int end);\\n\\nint main() {\\n    // Code goes here\\n    return 0;\\n}', 'output': 'The program should output the array in reverse order.', 'example': {'input': 'Array: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5], Size: 5', 'output': 'Reversed Array: [5, 4, 3, 2, 1]'}}", 'answer': 'Candidate: #include <stdio.h>\n\nvoid reverseArray(int arr[], int start, int end);\n\nint main() {\n    // Code goes here\n    return 0;\n} '}, {'question': "Interviewer: {'question': 'You are designing a mobile app interface in Figma and want to ensure that your design is responsive across different screen sizes. Which feature in Figma would you use to achieve this?', 'options': ['Auto Layout', 'Vector Networks', 'Smart Selection', 'Prototype Links'], 'correct_option': 'Auto Layout'}", 'answer': 'Candidate: Auto Layout '}, {'question': "Interviewer: {'question': 'While collaborating with your team on a Figma project, you need to leave feedback on a specific part of the design. What is the best way to do this directly within Figma?', 'options': ['Use the Comment tool to leave a note on the design', 'Send an email with your feedback', 'Export the design and annotate it in a separate tool', 'Schedule a meeting to discuss the feedback'], 'correct_option': 'Use the Comment tool to leave a note on the design'}", 'answer': 'Candidate: Use the Comment to